T1  - The predictive performance of the time-series model and the regression model of the income velocity of money: Evidence from five EEC countries
AU  - Ahking, Francis W.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 389
EP  - 415
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80060-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800606
AB  - This paper provides a comparative study of the relative performance of two models of the income velocity of money—a time-series model and a regression model, using quarterly data from five EEC countries. Our empirical results show that the regression model provides more accurate in-sample prediction than the time-series model. Out-of-sample, however, the regression model does not consistently outperform the time-series model. Instead, a linear composite perdiction combining the predictions from the time-series and the regression models appears to perform the best. Two other results of this paper are: (1) The stochastic structure of the income velocity of money can be adequately represented by a random-walk with drift model after seasonality is properly accounted for. (2) The regression model is temporally unstable for four of the five EEC countries.
ER  - 

