T1  - Optimal financial structure of finance companies in a regulated environment of a developing country
AU  - Calderón-Rossell, Jorge R.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 443
EP  - 457
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80063-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800631
AB  - Little is known about the regulatory framework for financial institutions in developing countries. In this paper, the effect of regulations in the financial structure of finance companies in a developing country is examined. The analysis suggests that regulations are so restrictive that they are reducing competition, limiting the mobilization of local resources, and inducing credit rationing in the financial system. The application of simple programming techniques to evaluate the regulatory framework is also demonstrated. Some policy recommendations and suggestions for further research are presented at the end.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the efficiency of the gold options market
AU  - Beckers, Stan
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 459
EP  - 470
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80064-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800643
AB  - Standardized gold options were introduced on the European Options Exchange in 1981. In the paper we investigate the efficiency of its pricing procedures. Specifically, the put-call parity conditions are verified. Virtually no evidence of profitable riskless arbitrage opportunities could be found. A riskless hedging strategy using the Black-Scholes call option pricing model was used to test market efficiency and to check for consistent discrepancies between model and market prices. Again, no evidence of market inefficiency could be found. However, there are indications that the Black-Scholes model is not appropriate to price out-of-the-money gold options. An alternative option pricing model is studied which may remedy this problem.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The natural taxation of capital gains and losses when incomes is taxed
AU  - Ball, Ray
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 471
EP  - 481
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80065-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800655
AB  - Income and capital gains are not independent components of returns to investors. Capital gains and losses are changes in present values of future income, so they are accompanied by changes in present values of future taxes. Their amounts are naturally reduced in the marketplace to the extent of the present value of the future tax obligations that they imply. A case for a separate capital gains tax lies in second-order effects, principally where income escapes taxation for administrative and other reasons. A case against a separate capital gains tax is that it is likely to tax gains at higher rates than losses, thereby giving the taxing authority a call option on value, so the effective incidence of the tax mitigates against risk-taking.
ER  - 

